# Java Collections ‚Äì Deque, ArrayDeque, List, ArrayList, LinkedList

---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£ Deque (Double Ended Queue)

### What is Deque?

* `Deque` extends `Queue`
* **Insertion & removal possible from both ends**
* Can behave as:

  * Queue (FIFO)
  * Stack (LIFO)

### Queue vs Deque

| Queue          | Deque                 |
| -------------- | --------------------- |
| Add ‚Üí last     | Add ‚Üí first / last    |
| Remove ‚Üí first | Remove ‚Üí first / last |

---

## 2Ô∏è‚É£ Deque Methods (Important)

### ‚ûï Insertion

| Method         | Position | Failure Behavior   |
| -------------- | -------- | ------------------ |
| `addFirst()`   | front    | throws exception   |
| `offerFirst()` | front    | returns true/false |
| `addLast()`    | back     | throws exception   |
| `offerLast()`  | back     | returns true/false |

### ‚ûñ Removal

| Method          | Position | Failure Behavior |
| --------------- | -------- | ---------------- |
| `removeFirst()` | front    | throws exception |
| `pollFirst()`   | front    | returns null     |
| `removeLast()`  | back     | throws exception |
| `pollLast()`    | back     | returns null     |

### üëÄ Examine (Peek)

| Method                       | Behavior                  |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------------- |
| `getFirst()` / `getLast()`   | throws exception if empty |
| `peekFirst()` / `peekLast()` | returns null if empty     |

---

## 3Ô∏è‚É£ Old Queue Methods in Deque

| Method     | Internally calls |
| ---------- | ---------------- |
| `add()`    | `addLast()`      |
| `offer()`  | `offerLast()`    |
| `remove()` | `removeFirst()`  |
| `poll()`   | `pollFirst()`    |
| `peek()`   | `peekFirst()`    |

‚û°Ô∏è Using only Queue methods ‚Üí behaves like normal FIFO queue

---

## 4Ô∏è‚É£ Deque as Stack

| Stack Operation | Deque Method              |
| --------------- | ------------------------- |
| push            | `addFirst()` / `push()`   |
| pop             | `removeFirst()` / `pop()` |

---

## 5Ô∏è‚É£ ArrayDeque

### About

* Concrete implementation of `Deque`
* Backed by **resizable array**
* Faster than `Stack`
* **Not thread-safe**

### Example ‚Äì Queue

```java
Deque<Integer> dq = new ArrayDeque<>();
dq.addLast(1);
dq.addLast(5);
dq.addLast(10);
System.out.println(dq.pollFirst()); // 1
```

### Example ‚Äì Stack

```java
Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
stack.push(1);
stack.push(5);
stack.push(10);
System.out.println(stack.pop()); // 10
```

### Time Complexity

| Operation         | Complexity     |
| ----------------- | -------------- |
| Insert first/last | O(1) amortized |
| Remove first/last | O(1)           |
| Peek              | O(1)           |
| Resize            | O(n) (rare)    |

---

## 6Ô∏è‚É£ Thread-safe Versions

| Collection    | Thread-safe Version     |
| ------------- | ----------------------- |
| PriorityQueue | `PriorityBlockingQueue` |
| ArrayDeque    | `ConcurrentLinkedDeque` |

---

## 7Ô∏è‚É£ List Interface

### What is List?

* Ordered collection
* Allows **duplicates**
* **Index-based access** (0-based)

### Difference: List vs Queue

| Queue                | List                |
| -------------------- | ------------------- |
| Add/remove ends only | Add/remove anywhere |
| FIFO                 | Index-based         |

---

## 8Ô∏è‚É£ List-Specific Methods

| Method              | Description                  |
| ------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| `add(index, e)`     | insert & shift right         |
| `set(index, e)`     | replace (no shift)           |
| `remove(index)`     | remove & shift left          |
| `get(index)`        | access element               |
| `indexOf()`         | first occurrence             |
| `lastIndexOf()`     | last occurrence              |
| `subList(from, to)` | view of list                 |
| `listIterator()`    | forward + backward iteration |

---

## 9Ô∏è‚É£ ArrayList

### Characteristics

* Backed by array
* Fast random access
* Slow insert/delete in middle
* **Not thread-safe**

### Example

```java
List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add(100);
list.add(200);
list.add(1, 150); // shift
```

### Time Complexity

| Operation         | Complexity     |
| ----------------- | -------------- |
| Add at end        | O(1) amortized |
| Add/remove middle | O(n)           |
| Get by index      | O(1)           |

### Thread-safe Version

* `CopyOnWriteArrayList`

---

## üîÅ ListIterator

### Why ListIterator?

* Traverse **forward + backward**
* Modify list during iteration

### Key Methods

| Method                         | Purpose               |
| ------------------------------ | --------------------- |
| `hasNext()` / `next()`         | forward               |
| `hasPrevious()` / `previous()` | backward              |
| `add(e)`                       | insert at cursor      |
| `set(e)`                       | replace last returned |

---

## üîó LinkedList

### Characteristics

* Doubly linked list
* Implements **List + Deque**
* Fast insert/delete
* Slow random access

### Example

```java
LinkedList<Integer> ll = new LinkedList<>();
ll.addFirst(100);
ll.addLast(300);
ll.add(1, 200);
```

### Time Complexity

| Operation             | Complexity |
| --------------------- | ---------- |
| Add/remove first/last | O(1)       |
| Add/remove by index   | O(n)       |
| Get by index          | O(n)       |

---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ Vector

### Characteristics

* Thread-safe ArrayList
* All methods synchronized
* Slower due to locking

```java
Vector<Integer> v = new Vector<>();
v.add(10);
```

---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ Stack

### About

* Extends `Vector`
* Thread-safe
* LIFO

```java
Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();
stack.push(10);
stack.pop();
```

---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£3Ô∏è‚É£ Summary Table

| Collection           | Thread-safe | Order | Null | Duplicate |
| -------------------- | ----------- | ----- | ---- | --------- |
| ArrayDeque           | ‚ùå           | Yes   | ‚ùå    | Yes       |
| LinkedList           | ‚ùå           | Yes   | Yes  | Yes       |
| ArrayList            | ‚ùå           | Yes   | Yes  | Yes       |
| CopyOnWriteArrayList | ‚úÖ           | Yes   | Yes  | Yes       |
| Vector               | ‚úÖ           | Yes   | Yes  | Yes       |
| Stack                | ‚úÖ           | LIFO  | Yes  | Yes       |

---

‚úÖ **This document covers Deque, ArrayDeque, List, ArrayList, LinkedList, Vector & Stack with concepts, methods, time complexity, thread-safety, and examples.**


Deque (interface)
 ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ ArrayDeque
 ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ LinkedList
 ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ ConcurrentLinkedDeque
 ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ LinkedBlockingDeque
Deque<Integer> dq = new ArrayDeque<>();
Deque<Integer> dq = new LinkedList<>();
Deque<Integer> dq = new ConcurrentLinkedDeque<>();
Deque<Integer> dq = new LinkedBlockingDeque<>();


Deque<Integer> dq = new ArrayDeque<>();
Notes

‚úî Fastest
‚ùå Not thread-safe
‚ùå No null

dq.addLast(1);   // queue
dq.addLast(2);

System.out.println(dq.removeFirst()); // 1

dq.push(10);     // stack
dq.push(20);

System.out.println(dq.pop()); // 20



LinkedList (List + Deque)
When to use
Need List + Deque behavior
‚úî Allows null
‚ùå Not thread-safe
‚ùå Slower than ArrayDeque
‚úî Implements List also

Frequent insert/remove

Deque<Integer> dq = new LinkedList<>();

dq.addFirst(1);
dq.addLast(2);

System.out.println(dq.removeLast()); // 2


‚ë¢ ConcurrentLinkedDeque (Thread-safe, Non-blocking)
When to use

Multi-threaded

High concurrency

Non-blocking
Notes

‚úî Thread-safe
‚úî Lock-free (CAS)
‚ùå No blocking operations
‚ùå No null


Deque<Integer> dq = new ConcurrentLinkedDeque<>();

dq.add(1);
dq.add(2);

System.out.println(dq.poll());


‚ë£ LinkedBlockingDeque (Thread-safe, Blocking)
When to use

Producer‚ÄìConsumer

Need blocking behavior

Notes

‚úî Thread-safe
‚úî Blocking operations
‚ùå Slightly slower
‚ùå No null
Deque<Integer> dq = new LinkedBlockingDeque<>(2);

dq.put(1);   // waits if full
dq.put(2);

System.out.println(dq.take()); // waits if empty


Deque has multiple implementations; ArrayDeque is the fastest but not the only one.